        "body": "Currently, the system does not provide a mechanism to identify and clean up leftover files from applications that have been uninstalled. These residual files can accumulate over time and occupy unnecessary storage.\n\nThis feature proposes an automated detection system that scans for:\n\nOrphaned files and folders linked to previously installed applications\nCached data, logs, and configuration files no longer associated with any active app\nBroken file references or unused dependencies\nExpected Behavior\nSystem should scan storage during setup or via manual trigger\nIdentify unused files based on:\nMissing parent application references\nLast access time and usage patterns\nProvide a categorized list of detected files (e.g., cache, config, logs)\nAllow users to review before deletion\nEnable one-click or selective removal\nEnsure safe deletion (no impact on active applications)\nAdditional Considerations\nMust avoid false positives (critical system files should not be flagged)\nInclude a rollback or backup option before deletion\nShould be lightweight and not impact system performance significantly\n\n**Use Case**\nUsers who frequently install/uninstall applications can reclaim storage space and maintain system cleanliness without manual file tracking.\n\n**Priority**\nMedium\n\n**Impact**\nImproves storage efficiency and system hygiene with minimal user effort\n\nhave a good day sir.",
